The press moves every six weeks and prints on paper bought in quantities too small to flag PIPSA's ledgers. What it prints is not triumphalism — she forbids the word *victoria* — but arithmetic: what the state spends hunting the columns against what it spends on clinics, names of the disappeared set in the smallest type so the list fits. The university reads it. The factories read the wage tables on the back page. The DFS reads it most carefully of all.

@la_fuga_accion
title: La fuga
subtitle: One name out of the state's hands: a prisoner walked out before the system closes over him.
card-image: img/cards/urbana.jpg
choose-if: advisor_action_timer == 0 and inteligencia >= 20 and funds >= 5
unavailable-subtitle: [? if advisor_action_timer > 0 : [+ advisor_action_timer +] months before next advisor action. ?][? if advisor_action_timer = 0 : A fuga runs on intelligence (20) and money (5 funds): guards have prices, floor plans have keepers. ?]
on-arrival: advisor_action_timer = 6; last_advisor_action = 1; funds -= 5; members += 1; represion += 3; expediente += 5; guerrilla_meter += 2

It is never dynamite; dynamite is for amateurs and corridos. It is a transfer order with one digit altered, a guard whose brother needed a surgery that was suddenly paid for, a laundry truck with a rebuilt floor. The compañero who was being asked questions in a building with no address wakes up in Guadalajara with new papers and an old debt. The state's fury is specific and budgeted; the network's lesson is priceless: *no one is left inside.* Nothing recruits like that sentence.
